1
00:02:46,320 --> 00:02:48,240
Goodbye. Till tomorrow.

2
00:02:49,240 --> 00:02:52,600
No, I'm taking a boat
to South America tonight.

3
00:02:52,600 --> 00:02:56,120
How long will you be gone?
A couple of months.

4
00:02:56,120 --> 00:03:00,520
I got the university to send me.
Why didn't you tell me?

5
00:03:01,720 --> 00:03:05,160
I wanted to cut it sharp
with a knife. But why?

6
00:03:05,160 --> 00:03:08,360
You know why. I don't like hiding.

7
00:03:08,360 --> 00:03:09,880
Why?

8
00:03:09,880 --> 00:03:11,920
Come with me.

9
00:03:11,920 --> 00:03:14,360
Just like that? Just like that.

10
00:03:14,360 --> 00:03:17,400
The captain will marry us
on the boat.

11
00:03:17,400 --> 00:03:20,800
Mark, it sounds so crazy
and wonderful but...

12
00:03:20,800 --> 00:03:23,120
You won't say a word to anybody,

13
00:03:23,120 --> 00:03:27,480
you'll go and pack and meet me
on the boat at eight o'clock.

14
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:33,360
Will I, Mark? Will you, Barbara?

15
00:03:35,160 --> 00:03:36,680
Yes!

16
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:18,600
WOMAN: Barbara, you're late.
I'm sorry, Aunt Eulah.

17
00:04:18,600 --> 00:04:21,040
Come here for a moment, my dear.

18
00:04:26,040 --> 00:04:31,080
We are having company for dinner.
I have invited Monsieur Duchaine.

19
00:04:32,720 --> 00:04:38,880
Monsieur Duchaine is a fine man,
my dear, a great gentleman.
Yes, Aunt Eulah.

20
00:04:38,880 --> 00:04:40,920
It is proper

21
00:04:40,920 --> 00:04:45,480
that money should be a large
consideration in your marriage.

22
00:04:45,480 --> 00:04:49,080
You may wear your new dress.
Thank you, Aunt Eulah.

23
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:52,600
MAN: Thank you, Robbie.

24
00:04:58,080 --> 00:05:00,120
In a hurry, Cousin?

25
00:05:00,120 --> 00:05:02,000
Paul!

26
00:05:03,600 --> 00:05:05,520
Yes, Mother.

27
00:05:10,320 --> 00:05:12,840
We're dining at home, you know.

28
00:05:14,840 --> 00:05:18,600
Aren't you wearing your new dress,
Cousin dear?

29
00:05:21,600 --> 00:05:25,640
Is it necessary to pack a suitcase
to go down to dinner?

30
00:05:27,720 --> 00:05:29,760
I'm going away, Paul.

31
00:05:29,760 --> 00:05:32,440
Oh, that's what the suitcase is for.

32
00:05:32,440 --> 00:05:39,720
Is it that research fellow, Barbara,
from the university? How did you
know? I thought nobody knew.

33
00:05:39,720 --> 00:05:42,320
Well, you're my favourite cousin!

34
00:05:42,320 --> 00:05:47,120
Is it by any chance the boat
that sails tonight at eight o'clock?

35
00:05:47,120 --> 00:05:52,160
I'd better see you off, it's not au
fait for a young lady to go alone.

36
00:05:52,160 --> 00:05:56,920
What's the matter? You're not
going to tell your mother?

37
00:05:56,920 --> 00:05:59,000
Her heart.

38
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:06,560
As a matter of a fact she won't
have an attack immediately, not
until your entire story comes out.

39
00:06:06,560 --> 00:06:12,040
You don't intend, of course, to
come back to New Orleans. Why not?

40
00:06:12,040 --> 00:06:18,560
You'd be a figure of some notoriety.
People would dig into your...
shall we say, ancestry.

41
00:06:21,400 --> 00:06:25,520
Well, Mother's old, she hadn't
many years to live anyhow.

42
00:06:25,520 --> 00:06:29,200
I don't blame you for wanting
to live your own life.

43
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:31,240
You don't blame me?

44
00:06:31,240 --> 00:06:36,600
You don't blame anyone as long
as it doesn't interfere with you.

45
00:06:47,400 --> 00:06:52,040
I don't know whether you should
write Dear Mark or Dear Doctor.

46
00:06:52,040 --> 00:06:56,400
"Darling". Of course,
that's much more simple and direct.

47
00:06:56,400 --> 00:06:58,440
Very sweet.

48
00:06:58,440 --> 00:07:00,800
Very commendable.

49
00:07:00,800 --> 00:07:04,320
And you will always be here,
waiting.

50
00:07:04,320 --> 00:07:11,280
Mother might ask questions
if you whisper with the servants.
I'll see that it gets to the ship.

51
00:07:11,280 --> 00:07:13,240
Promise, Paul.

52
00:07:13,240 --> 00:07:15,120
I promise, Barbara.

53
00:07:15,120 --> 00:07:18,680
You'll be lovely in your new dress,
Cousin dear!

54
00:07:27,480 --> 00:07:30,960
< Lower your gangplank!
Lower your gangplank!

55
00:07:34,360 --> 00:07:36,400
< Stand by your lines!

56
00:07:36,400 --> 00:07:41,600
AUNT: Nowadays, Mr Duchaine,
it's considered old-fashioned

57
00:07:41,600 --> 00:07:48,320
to be proud of one's origins.
Well, Madame, I prefer to be
considered old-fashioned.

58
00:07:48,320 --> 00:07:53,520
I feel it's our duty to remember
our heritage and be proud of it.

59
00:07:57,120 --> 00:07:59,600
SHIP'S HOOTER BLOWS

60
00:08:03,160 --> 00:08:10,120
You know, Clay, whenever Barbara
hears a ship's whistle at
eight o'clock, she spills her soup.

61
00:08:19,280 --> 00:08:22,560
# The spirits creep

62
00:08:22,560 --> 00:08:25,480
# The ghosties run

63
00:08:25,480 --> 00:08:29,320
# The skeletons rattle and moan

64
00:08:29,320 --> 00:08:33,360
# The goblins holler... #
Where's 39, Elisa Street?

65
00:08:33,360 --> 00:08:37,320
# Takes magic to scare off
dead bones... # Thank you.

66
00:08:37,320 --> 00:08:44,280
Buy a cute little skeleton
for Halloween? Do I look like a man
who'd buy a skeleton? No, sir.

67
00:08:46,480 --> 00:08:50,480
Why don't you look
where you're going? Why don't YOU!

68
00:08:54,280 --> 00:08:58,200
# Goblins holler
on All Saints Eve... #

69
00:08:59,320 --> 00:09:04,400
Is this number 39? Yes, sir.
Does a Barbara Beaurevel live here?

70
00:09:04,400 --> 00:09:10,440
All the Beaurevels live here, sir.
Miss, Madame and the Mister.
Thank you.

71
00:09:13,040 --> 00:09:18,160
My dear man, I suggest that
you find yourself an attorney.

72
00:09:20,760 --> 00:09:23,520
"Luther Toplady. Attorney at law."

73
00:09:23,520 --> 00:09:29,840
Well, Mr Luther Toplady,
I don't think you have any action
against me.

74
00:09:29,840 --> 00:09:34,320
I'm not even interested in you,
unless your name is Barbara.

75
00:09:34,320 --> 00:09:41,640
Barbara? I've come all the way from
California to see her. Paul! Yes,
Mother? I wish to see the gentleman.

76
00:09:41,640 --> 00:09:47,880
Mr Toplady. From California.
Your business, please?
Are you Barbara Beaurevel?

77
00:09:47,880 --> 00:09:55,000
We are the only Beaurevels in New
Orleans. I'm tracing the relatives
of a lady who died. A Mrs Crandall.

78
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:59,840
We have no Crandalls in our family.
This is a matter of a bequest.

79
00:09:59,840 --> 00:10:04,200
I've traced a Barbara Beaurevel
to this address. Good day.

80
00:10:04,200 --> 00:10:10,920
Mother, you might listen.
All the diamonds in Africa couldn't
join Carrie Crandall to my family.

81
00:10:10,920 --> 00:10:16,960
I'm sure you'll forgive me
for asking how you knew
I meant Carrie Crandall?

82
00:10:16,960 --> 00:10:22,840
I see that you have your hat...
I came 3,000 miles to see
Barbara Beaurevel and...

83
00:10:22,840 --> 00:10:24,880
Barbara Beaurevel is dead!

84
00:10:31,280 --> 00:10:33,320
Good day, Madam.

85
00:10:37,040 --> 00:10:44,720
I'm afraid you don't understand our
traditions. The older I grow, the
more I see, the less I understand.

86
00:10:44,720 --> 00:10:50,600
Yes, I'm sure life
is much more simple in California.
Aunt Eulah!

87
00:10:50,600 --> 00:10:53,800
Isn't that.... Goodbye, Mr Toplady!

88
00:10:53,800 --> 00:11:00,480
Aunt Eulah... Barbara,
do not come rushing down the stairs,
it's extremely unbecoming.

89
00:11:00,480 --> 00:11:08,600
You saw the gentleman who just left
this house? Yes. You're not to see
him again even if he asks for you.

90
00:11:08,600 --> 00:11:15,640
He talked about your unsavoury
relation. Paul! Can't we even
shake Barbara's skeleton in private?

91
00:11:15,640 --> 00:11:21,400
There's some sordid bequest
I said you were dead.
We don't need the money.

92
00:11:21,400 --> 00:11:28,440
That's not funny, Paul. I agree.
I'd like permission to meet
Cousin Philippe's boat. Alone?

93
00:11:28,440 --> 00:11:34,600
It's just to meet a boat.
You didn't see him off when
he left for South America. May I?

94
00:11:34,600 --> 00:11:38,240
Clay wouldn't like it.
I'm not married to Clay!

95
00:11:38,240 --> 00:11:44,480
He can't object if you accompany
her. I shall be happy to carry you
to the boat, Cousin.

96
00:11:44,480 --> 00:11:51,520
Paul is always charming! Tell
Philippe he must come to dinner!
I'll see if the carriage is ready.

97
00:11:52,600 --> 00:11:54,040
Paul!

98
00:11:54,040 --> 00:11:55,680
Mmm?

99
00:12:20,480 --> 00:12:22,920
The gangplank isn't down yet.

100
00:12:22,920 --> 00:12:29,000
You know, when you're eager
and excited, you're wonderfully
pretty! Am I, Paul?

101
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:33,760
I wish I had a nice dress. I could
do with some new shoes, myself.

102
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:40,280
Oh, dear, what a lucky fellow he is.
Who? My cousin Philippe, of course.

103
00:12:40,280 --> 00:12:44,400
It's a pity you haven't got money,
I'd marry you myself.

104
00:12:44,400 --> 00:12:48,920
Oh, that's a very interesting idea!
They're coming ashore!

105
00:12:48,920 --> 00:12:55,240
You're the most attractive woman
I've ever seen. You should make
something out of it.

106
00:12:55,240 --> 00:12:57,880
I'm sure you'll make sure that I do!

107
00:13:05,160 --> 00:13:09,080
Here he is, right in front of you.
Hello, Philippe!

108
00:13:09,080 --> 00:13:11,640
How extremely nice of you to come!

109
00:13:11,640 --> 00:13:19,320
Barbara insisted. Welcome home,
Philippe. My dear beautiful cousin!
Aunt Eulah wants you to dinner.

110
00:13:19,320 --> 00:13:21,480
How extremely kind of her.

111
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:30,440
Oh, you want to get
through customs quickly.

112
00:13:30,440 --> 00:13:36,240
Paul, help Philippe.
I imagine you'll find something
to do till I get back.

113
00:13:36,240 --> 00:13:38,280
Mark!

114
00:13:38,280 --> 00:13:44,880
Darling, it's been so long! Has it?
Two months can be a lifetime.
I never knew that before.

115
00:13:44,880 --> 00:13:52,400
How is your dear family(?)
Oh, Corinne, this is Miss Beaurevel.
My wife.

116
00:13:52,400 --> 00:13:54,240
How do you do?

117
00:13:54,240 --> 00:14:00,520
How do you do? I believe
you're the first native
of New Orleans my wife has met.

118
00:14:00,520 --> 00:14:05,560
It's like eating the core of the
apple before taking the first bite.

119
00:14:05,560 --> 00:14:11,600
I'm glad we married
before coming here
if they're all as pretty as you are.

120
00:14:11,600 --> 00:14:15,720
They're not, and besides,
they're most undependable,

121
00:14:15,720 --> 00:14:22,560
wouldn't you say so, Miss Beaurevel?
Would you, Dr Lucas?
Possibly only the great beauties.

122
00:14:22,560 --> 00:14:26,560
Delighted to have seen you,
Miss Beaurevel. Goodbye.

123
00:14:29,160 --> 00:14:35,120
Hello, Dean Casley.
I didn't expect to be met.
I'm anxious to get your reports.

124
00:14:47,240 --> 00:14:49,760
Barbara, you must be practical.

125
00:14:49,760 --> 00:14:54,120
You're well out of it  the man
has neither family nor money.

126
00:14:54,120 --> 00:15:01,560
I admit he might be famous some day
but let other people have the fame,
luxury is much more pleasant.

127
00:15:01,560 --> 00:15:05,320
I don't know what's going on
under that pretty hat,

128
00:15:05,320 --> 00:15:09,760
but Mother is right when she talks
about a good name. Paul...

129
00:15:09,760 --> 00:15:15,080
Hmm? Do you mind if I don't come in?
I'd like to take a drive. Alone.

130
00:15:16,080 --> 00:15:21,200
Don't do any thinking, it's bad for
the complexion. All right, Pappy.

131
00:15:21,200 --> 00:15:23,240
Where to, Miss Barbie?

132
00:15:23,240 --> 00:15:25,280
I'll tell you on the way.

133
00:15:35,080 --> 00:15:38,120
Is Mr Toplady registered here, sir?

134
00:15:38,120 --> 00:15:45,240
Yes. Would you ask him to come
to the ladies' parlour, please?
Yes, madam. This way, Miss Barbie.

135
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:56,440
Your name IS Barbara. Wait
outside the door, Pappy. I'll be
in shouting distance, Miss Barbie.

136
00:15:56,440 --> 00:15:59,400
Thank you, that's a great comfort.

137
00:16:04,080 --> 00:16:06,880
Won't you sit down, Miss Beaurevel?

138
00:16:08,720 --> 00:16:12,160
May I get you some coffee?
No, thank you.

139
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:19,080
Do you know
what Carrie Crandall was?

140
00:16:19,080 --> 00:16:25,480
She was a sister of James McDougall
who has died leaving a bequest
to her heirs.

141
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:30,080
I am Carrie Crandall's
granddaughter.

142
00:16:33,200 --> 00:16:34,720
Well?

143
00:16:34,720 --> 00:16:42,960
I'm delighted to find someone who
admits Carrie Crandall ever existed!
My aunt has been deathly afraid

144
00:16:42,960 --> 00:16:46,600
that it would come out
that my grandmother was...

145
00:16:46,600 --> 00:16:48,640
Such a notorious woman.

146
00:16:48,640 --> 00:16:52,080
They even point at her grave
and make jokes.

147
00:16:52,080 --> 00:16:55,760
Even now I'm not sure
that Aunt Eulah isn't right.

148
00:16:55,760 --> 00:16:57,800
If the truth were known,

149
00:16:57,800 --> 00:17:04,040
I couldn't live in New Orleans
any more. Would it be so terrible?
I think I should die!

150
00:17:04,040 --> 00:17:11,360
I don't think you'll be forced into
an early suicide. There's no need
of court action or publicity.

151
00:17:11,360 --> 00:17:16,520
Carrie Crandall's daughter entered
into a convent under a false name

152
00:17:16,520 --> 00:17:20,000
and married your father
under that false name,

153
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:23,880
I have documented proof of this.
Furthermore, you resemble
your grandmother greatly.

154
00:17:23,880 --> 00:17:26,320
You knew her?

155
00:17:26,320 --> 00:17:28,320
That's how I recognised you.

156
00:17:28,320 --> 00:17:32,360
Imagine her with your complexion,
with your proud look.

157
00:17:33,880 --> 00:17:36,320
I didn't know I had a proud look.

158
00:17:36,320 --> 00:17:38,360
Just as she had.

159
00:17:38,360 --> 00:17:43,560
She married a gambler. He left
her before the child was born.

160
00:17:43,560 --> 00:17:48,120
She did whatever she had to
for the welfare of the little girl,

161
00:17:48,120 --> 00:17:51,560
even to hiding her own motherhood
and love.

162
00:17:51,560 --> 00:17:53,960
But she was... Yes, she was.

163
00:17:53,960 --> 00:17:58,600
So if because of what she was
you refuse the inheritance... No!

164
00:17:58,600 --> 00:18:05,840
In spite of your aunt's wishes
you still want the money? Yes.
The estate can be easily liquidated,

165
00:18:05,840 --> 00:18:08,400
it comes from gold. Is there much?

166
00:18:08,400 --> 00:18:11,160
By certain standards, yes. How much?

167
00:18:11,160 --> 00:18:14,880
A little over...900,000 dollars.

168
00:18:16,200 --> 00:18:18,240
When do I get it?

169
00:18:18,240 --> 00:18:22,440
I'll have the papers ready
for your signature tomorrow.

170
00:18:22,440 --> 00:18:26,560
At first I thought Toplady
was a silly name but now I love it!

171
00:18:29,560 --> 00:18:31,760
Miss Beaurevel... Yes?

172
00:18:31,760 --> 00:18:35,880
I'm not sure I like the feeling
behind your smile.

173
00:18:35,880 --> 00:18:38,640
I trust you'll use the money wisely?

174
00:18:38,640 --> 00:18:41,920
I will. I can promise you I will!

175
00:18:48,040 --> 00:18:52,320
CLAY: Why should I finance you
in a brokerage house, Paul?

176
00:18:52,320 --> 00:18:56,040
I'd be very good at it
and would make you a lot of money.

177
00:18:56,040 --> 00:18:59,880
I don't need any more money.
That's where we differ.

178
00:18:59,880 --> 00:19:07,400
Miss Beaurevel. Mr Duchaine has been
waiting for you, Barbara. I'm sorry.
You're always worth waiting for.

179
00:19:07,400 --> 00:19:12,400
Would you mind if I talked to
Barbara alone? Why, of course not.

180
00:19:14,960 --> 00:19:19,320
Well? I wanted to make sure
about the costume ball tonight.

181
00:19:19,320 --> 00:19:23,400
I hadn't forgotten.
I'll come by at ten. No, Clay.

182
00:19:23,400 --> 00:19:28,440
There's somewhere I'd like
to go first, alone. Is that wise?

183
00:19:28,440 --> 00:19:31,080
It's what I'm going to do.

184
00:19:31,080 --> 00:19:34,840
There's something different
about you, Barbara.

185
00:19:36,480 --> 00:19:38,920
I don't know quite how to say it.

186
00:19:38,920 --> 00:19:43,440
It's as though there was a secret
that warms you.

187
00:19:43,440 --> 00:19:45,480
Do you mind?

188
00:19:45,480 --> 00:19:47,920
I mind nothing that you do or are.

189
00:19:47,920 --> 00:19:53,360
Even the fact that my family wants
me to marry you for your money?

190
00:19:53,360 --> 00:19:56,480
If being poor puts them on my side,

191
00:19:56,480 --> 00:19:58,840
I'm glad they're poor.

192
00:19:59,920 --> 00:20:02,080
If you'll marry me, Barbara,

193
00:20:02,080 --> 00:20:09,560
I'll do anything you want. I'll be
anything you want. I like you, Clay,
better than I ever have before.

194
00:20:09,560 --> 00:20:11,600
Goodbye, Clay.

195
00:20:13,480 --> 00:20:15,920
Say goodbye to your aunt for me.

196
00:20:20,320 --> 00:20:27,560
You must be out of your mind.
You WERE listening, weren't you?
Where are you going before the ball?

197
00:20:27,560 --> 00:20:34,240
If you listened carefully,
you'll know I didn't even tell Clay.
You'll lose him.

198
00:20:34,240 --> 00:20:37,880
And then where would
your brokerage business be?

199
00:20:37,880 --> 00:20:44,920
We don't approve of your going
anywhere alone. That's too bad
because nobody's coming with me!

200
00:20:47,400 --> 00:20:51,320
PEOPLE SING AND SHOUT

201
00:21:03,080 --> 00:21:06,120
CHILDREN SHOUT: Trick or treat!

202
00:21:12,880 --> 00:21:19,920
BOY SINGS: # Light a candle
for your loved one... #

203
00:21:24,640 --> 00:21:27,160
MARK: You explain it to her, Dean.

204
00:21:27,160 --> 00:21:33,240
All Souls' Eve is what you call
Halloween up north. To us
it's a religious occasion

205
00:21:33,240 --> 00:21:39,160
but there are enough
goblins and imps so that
we don't treat it too soberly.

206
00:21:42,400 --> 00:21:48,000
..On this night one lights a candle
to one's dear departed.

207
00:22:08,920 --> 00:22:10,960
Are you alone?

208
00:22:13,200 --> 00:22:15,240
Isn't everyone?

209
00:22:15,240 --> 00:22:21,960
You're a philosopher now?
I thought you didn't believe in
these barbaric ceremonies. I don't.

210
00:22:24,240 --> 00:22:26,280
Then why did you come?

211
00:22:26,280 --> 00:22:32,880
My wife. Strangers like to see
the superstitious customs
of this primitive society.

212
00:22:32,880 --> 00:22:40,280
That's an interesting smile you're
wearing. Do you still want to cut
it sharp with a knife? Cut what?

213
00:22:40,280 --> 00:22:42,880
You don't remember. Suppose I do?

214
00:22:42,880 --> 00:22:47,720
It was such a long time ago. A
lifetime. We barely knew each other.

215
00:22:47,720 --> 00:22:54,200
We only saw each other every day
for month after month.
And still I didn't know you.

216
00:22:54,200 --> 00:22:58,040
That may be because you're afraid
to know yourself.

217
00:22:58,040 --> 00:23:00,600
I found out one thing... Oh?

218
00:23:00,600 --> 00:23:04,040
You're not much of a letter writer,
are you?

219
